/* How this works and what I learned:
1: Include string.h and stdio.h for strlen() and printf() respectively.
    - I had forgotten how much of C requires including a library of some sort.
2: Declare the int main function because that's required with C. Did it as an int because reasons:
    - That just seems to be how people do it. (Original reason)
    - It lets you return 0 to tell any other program using this that it was successful. (Also original reason, though I don't know why any other program would use this.)
    - Also apparently C++ requires main() to be an int function. (Just learned that while writing this)
3: Set a char variable (puzinp) to be the input string the AoC website gave me. Makes the program generally less useful but it works.
    - I honestly don't remember why I did it like this instead of just using a scanf(). Maybe it wouldn't let me scanf() a string of undefined size? I don't remember.
    - When I first wrote this I was planning on *either* including stdio.h and getting the input from a scanf() *or* just including it as a pre-defined array. Ended up doing both for some reason.
4: Set a lot of int variables: (5)
    - int floor to track the result number.
    - int basetime to track the position in the string where floor first reaches -1.
    - int basebefore to track if -1 has been reached yet, to avoid printing basetime *every time* floor reaches -1. Which happens a lot.
    - int len because I read that using strlen() directly in a for loop will run strlen() every single loop, which makes things a lot slower.
    - int i because trying to declare it in the for loop it's used in gave me an error when I tried. Further research tells me that this is only required prior to C99.
5: Run a for loop that iterates over the entire input string one time.
    5.1: Increase basetime by 1. Done at the beginning of the loop because otherwise basetime will be off by 1 when it's printed.
    5.2: If the current character of puzinp equals ( increase floor by 1.
    5.3: If the current character of puzinp equals ) decrease floor by 1.
    5.4: If floor = -1 and basebefore = 0, print basetime and set basebefore to 1 so this won't happen again.
    - Very important, always use *two* equal signs or other such things in if statements, otherwise it doesn't work right.
6: Once the for loop is done, print floor.
7: return 0 for reasons mentioned above.
- It's been too long since I last used C, I forgot that you need to put a ; after *everything.*
- I'm just glad this didn't require anything involving memory allocation or file manipulation.
*/
